Pensioners could be entitled to a weekly boost in their income through Pension Credit. The benefit is paid by the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) and could help low income pensioners. The amount someone can get through Pension Credit depends on which version they receive. There are two types of Pension Credit, known as Guarantee Credit and Savings Credit. Guarantee Credit provides the highest level of support. READ MORE: ‘Never paid pensioners more!’ State pension frustration as sum will not increase to £380 Guarantee Credit could top up claimants’ weekly income to: Savings Credit provides a lower weekly amount to people who have more income. DON'T MISSPensioners lose £8,000 of state pension as expats see sums frozen - 'end this injustice' [PENSION]Woman in tears at £1.4m inheritance tax bill from HMRC ‘Parents have already paid taxes!' [TAX]Fury at plans to BAN gas boilers and force Brits to install £10,000 heat pumps [REACTION] Recipients could get up to: Pensioners could also get extra amounts if they have other responsibilities and costs, such as caring responsibilities or disabilities. People who claim Pension Credit also qualify for other forms of support, such as: Claims for Pension Credit can be submitted online via the official Government website. People can also apply by calling the Pension Credit claim line at 0800 99 1234. To apply by post, pensioners can print out and fill in the Pension Credit claim form or call the claim line to request a form. The completed claim form should be sent to the Pension Service. Applicants will have their income assessed when applying to determine whether they are eligible for support.